{"cursor":"5353","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type = monarch name = Henry I image = Enrique I de Castilla.jpg imgw = 150px\n| caption = succession = King of Castile and Toledo reign = 5 October 1214\n| – 6 June 1217 coronation = predecessor = Alfonso VIII successor =\n| Berengaria spouse = Mafalda of Portugal issue = issue-link = issue-pipe =\n| house = House of Burgundy father = Alfonso VIII of Castile mother = Eleanor of\n| England birth_date = birth_place = Valladolid death_date = death_place =\n| Palencia burial_date = burial_place = Las Huelgas, Burgos religion = Roman\n| Catholicism }}\n\n'Henry I of Castile' (14 April 1204 â 6 June 1217) was king of Castile. He was\nthe son of Alfonso VIII of Castile and his wife was Eleanor Plantagenet,\n(daughter of Henry II of England and Eleanor of Aquitaine). PrevitÃ©-Orton,\nCharles William, The shorter Cambridge Medieval History, (Cambridge University\nPress, 1952), 828.\n\nIn 1211, Henry became heir to the throne when his older brother Ferdinand\nsuddenly died.\n\nWhen his father died, in 1214, Henry was just 10 years old, so the regency\nwas assumed by Henry's older sister Berengaria of Castile, wife of Alfonso\nIX of Leon.\n\nIn 1215, Henry married Mafalda of Portugal, daughter of Sancho I of Portugal. As\nhe was very young, the marriage was not consummated, and it was dissolved in\n1216 by Pope Innocent III on grounds on consanguinity.\n\nHenry I died in Palencia in 1217 at the age of 13, killed by a tile coming off a\nroof. His sister Berengaria succeeded him, before renouncing the throne in favor\nof her son Ferdinand III. Craig Taylor, Debating the Hundred Years War,\n(Cambridge University Press, 2006), 87. His body was interred at Las\nHuelgas monastery in Burgos. Enrique I, King of Castile, Theresa M. Vann,\n'Medieval Iberia: An Encyclopedia', Ed. E. Gerli, (Routledge, 2003), 303.\n","linknr":225,"url":"Henry_I_of_Castile","recorded":1375065657,"links":["/w/index.